---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "About Perfect Pace - Advanced Race Strategy Planner";
const description = "Learn how Perfect Pace uses GAP (Grade Adjusted Pace) and elevation data to create the perfect pacing strategy for your next race.";
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <div class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-3xl mx-auto pt-8">
    <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold bg-clip-text text-transparent bg-gradient-to-r from-primary to-secondary mb-6">
      About Perfect Pace
    </h1>

    <p class="lead text-lg text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300">
      Perfect Pace is a specialized tool designed to help runners executing their race strategy with precision.
      Unlike simple pace calculators, we take into account the <strong>elevation profile</strong> of your race
      to calculate the <a href="https://fellrnr.com/wiki/Grade_Adjusted_Pace" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-primary hover:underline">Grade Adjusted Pace (GAP)</a>.
    </p>

    <div class="my-8 p-6 bg-surface-light dark:bg-surface-dark rounded-xl border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700 shadow-sm">
      <h3 className="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Why use Perfect Pace?</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 list-disc list-inside text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
        <li><strong>Physics-based Pacing:</strong> Uses Minetti's energy cost equations to adjust pace for uphills and downhills.</li>
        <li><strong>Smart Strategies:</strong> Choose between Constant Effort, Negative Split, or custom strategies like "The Crash" or "The Rise".</li>
        <li><strong>Actionable Data:</strong> Export your plan to your Garmin/Coros via CSV or print a waterproof wristband.</li>
        <li><strong>Privacy First:</strong> All processing happens in your browser. Your GPX files are never uploaded to a server.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">How to use it</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-secondary">1. Define your Goal</h3>
        <p>Set your target time and the total distance. Be realistic based on your current fitness.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-secondary">2. Upload a GPX (Recommended)</h3>
        <p>
          Upload the route file (GPX) of your race. This allows the algorithm to detect hills and adjust the pace accordingly.
          You'll run slower on uphills and faster on downhills while maintaining a constant physiological effort.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-secondary">3. Choose a Strategy</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Steady:</strong> Constant effort throughout the race.<br/>
          <strong>Negative Split:</strong> Start conservative and speed up in the second half.<br/>
          <strong>The Rise:</strong> A more aggressive negative split.<br/>
          <strong>The Crash:</strong> Banking time early (risky!).
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <hr class="my-10 border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700" />

    <div class="text-center space-y-6">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">Support the Project</h2>
      <p>
        Perfect Pace is free and open source. If it helped you achieve a PR or qualify for Boston,
        consider buying me a coffee to keep the servers running (and the developer caffeinated).
      </p>

      <a href="https://www.buymeacoffee.com/maiobarbero" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="inline-block transition-transform hover:-translate-y-1">
        <img src="https://cdn.buymeacoffee.com/buttons/v2/default-yellow.png" alt="Buy Me A Coffee" class="h-14 w-auto shadow-lg rounded-lg" />
      </a>

      <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 mt-4">
        Developed by <a href="https://github.com/maio" target="_blank" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Maio</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
